result.execSummary:
The defendant Jeremiah P Boblett was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Manufacture/Deliver THC (>200-1000g) [Modifiers: PTAC, as a Party to a Crime], a class H felony, Wisconsin Statutes 961.41(1)(h)2.

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

supervisions.notes:
Must report to Probation today (9/30/2016).
***Per Court order on 8/29/2019, probationary term extended until 9/30/2020.***
Must complete an AODA assessment and compliance.

miscConds.notes: $290.60 fine/costs to be paid to the Clerk of Court Office by payment plan of $25.00 per month commencing on November 1, 2016 and the first of each month thereafter until paid in full. Failure to pay will be civil judgment.

Must provide DNA sample and pay the $250.00 DNA surcharge to the COCC by payment plan of $25.00 per month commencing on November 1, 2016 and the first of each month thereafter until paid in full. Failure to pay will be civil judgment.   Defendant may request expungement of the DNA sample under Wis. Stat. 165.77(4) by petitioning the Wisconsin Department of Justice. Expungement of DNA is NOT a court process. 
For information see: http://www.doj.state.wi.us/dles/crime-labs/clb-forms.
May not possess or use firearms or body armor.
Absolute sobriety. Cannot vote. Cannot hold elective office. If not a U.S. Citizen, may face deportation. No drug use.
Must write an apology letter to victim and give to District Attorney Office.

**$10,314.00 Restitution, plus 10% surcharge of $1,031.40, for a total of $11,345.40.  Bond of $1,500.00 to be applied to Restitution and paid directly to the District Attorney's Office.  Probation to collect remaining balance of Restitution in the amount of $8,814.00, plus 10% surcharge of $881.40, for a total of $9,695.40 in a payment plan of $150.00 per month beginning 12/01/2016 and due on the first of each month thereafter until paid in full.**
***Per Court order on 8/29/2019, payment plan is reaffirmed.***
